<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-541-704  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 541 704.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  May 14 1990 n270 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS on the hiring line: IS executives need to become betterrecruiters.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kay, Sheryl.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The increasing importance of information systems (IS), higheremployee turnover, and the decreasing number of computer sciencegraduates is making staff recruitment a high priority for ISmanagers.andP;  Demand for systems analysts will increase by nearly 76percent and 70 percent for programmers by the turn of the century,while only 2 percent to 3 percent of college graduates will becomputer science majors.andP;  MIS managers will need to put as muchtime into hiring staff as in purchasing new systems.andP;  CIOs rankedstaffing issues among the highest priorities in a recent survey.andO;The survey also found turnover in the computer department to betoo high.andP;  The cost of hiring the wrong employee is also rising.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISHiringEmployment OpportunityTrendsInformation Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>